itle":"Author/Jae-Hoon Choi","target":"Author/Jae-Hoon Choi","line":95},{"title":"Author/Jae-Hoon Choi","target":"Author/Jae-Hoon Choi","line":96},{"title":"Author/Hirofumi Hirai","target":"Author/Hirofumi Hirai","line":97},{"title":"Author/Hirofumi Hirai","target":"Author/Hirofumi Hirai","line":98},{"title":"Author/Hirokazu Kawagishi","target":"Author/Hirokazu Kawagishi","line":99},{"title":"Author/Hirokazu Kawagishi","target":"Author/Hirokazu Kawagishi","line":100},{"title":"PDF","target":"biblib/wu_erinaceolactones_2015/wu_erinaceolactones_2015.pdf","line":102}],"metadata":{"id":"wu_erinaceolactones_2015","type":"article-journal","title":"Erinaceolactones A to C, from the culture broth of Hericium erinaceus.","issued":{"date-parts":[[2015]]},"DOI":"10.1021/np500623s","container-title":"Journal of Natural Products","abstract":"Three novel compounds, erinaceolactones A to C (1–3), and a known compound (4) were isolated from the culture broth of Hericium erinaceus. The planar structures of 1–3 were determined by the interpretation of spectroscopic data. The absolute configuration of 3 was determined by X-ray crystallography. Although compound 4 had been synthesized, it was isolated from a natural source for the first time. In the bioassay examining plant-growth regulatory activity of these compounds (1–4) and other components of the fungus (5–8), compounds 1, 2, and 4–8 suppressed the growth of lettuce.","tags":["#literature_note"],"author":[{"family":"Wu","given":"Jing","literal":""},{"family":"Wu","given":"Jing","literal":""},{"family":"Tokunaga","given":"Taiki","literal":""},{"family":"Tokunaga","given":"Taiki","literal":""},{"family":"Kondo","given":"Mitsuru","literal":""},{"family":"Kondo","given":"Mitsuru","literal":""},{"family":"Kondo","given":"Mitsuru","literal":""},{"family":"Kondo","given":"Mitsuru","literal":""},{"family":"Ishigami","given":"Kota","literal":""},{"family":"Ishigami","given":"Kota","literal":""},{"family":"Tokuyama","given":"Shogo","litera